) is an individual form, sometimes prevalent in some places: it shows a wide, dark terminal fascia on the forewing and a weakly marked underside on the hindwing, which is orange-yellow, scattered with dark vertical stripes, with barely perceptible lighter radiating streaks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="239">
In the female genitalia signum small (0.8-0.9 mm, exceptionally 1.2 mm in a female from the Apennines near Bologna: see Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 3" captionStartId="T3" captionText="Table 3. Analysis of the morphological characters observed in the material examined." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/BECE0A14670BA886ABAB732163BB1ADE" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" tableUuid="BECE0A14670BA886ABAB732163BB1ADE">3</tableCitation>
). Bullae tympani with a roundish lobe (absent in a female from the same locality: see Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 3" captionStartId="T3" captionText="Table 3. Analysis of the morphological characters observed in the material examined." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/BECE0A14670BA886ABAB732163BB1ADE" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" tableUuid="BECE0A14670BA886ABAB732163BB1ADE">3</tableCitation>
). The specimens from northern Piedmont (Graian and Pennine Alps) were not dissected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="239" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="239">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="239">
France SE, Italy (Piedmont, Liguria, Tuscany, Emilia-Romagna: see Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of the taxa of the complex limbaria / roraria in northern Italy (the open symbols refer to records not verified by the authors)." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.43.46559.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/439081" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">2</figureCitation>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Leraut, P" journalOrPublisher="Editions, Verrieres le Buisson, France" pageId="17" pageNumber="244" refId="B22" refString="Leraut, P, 2009. Moths of Europe 2. Geometrid moths. N.A.P. Editions, Verrieres le Buisson, France" title="Moths of Europe 2. Geometrid moths. N. A. P." year="2009">Leraut (2009)</bibRefCitation>
its distribution in France is limited to the southern Alps; we have confirmation for the following departments: 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Drôme">Drome</normalizedToken>
: Montagne de Chamouse (
<bibRefCitation author="Skou, P" journalOrPublisher="Brill, Leiden" pageId="17" pageNumber="244" refId="B37" refString="Skou, P, Sihvonen, P, 2015. Ennominae I. In: Hausmann A (Ed.) The Geometrid Moths of Europe 5. Brill, Leiden" title="Ennominae I. In: Hausmann A (Ed.) The Geometrid Moths of Europe 5." year="2015">Skou and Sihvonen 2015</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 2, fig. 18c, e), Vaucluse, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence, Alpes-Maritimes, Var. In Piedmont it occurs mainly in the south, from the Maritime Alps to the Apennines; according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Flamigni, C" journalOrPublisher="Natura Edizioni Scientifiche di Alfonso Iorio, Bologna" pageId="16" pageNumber="243" refId="B8" refString="Flamigni, C, Fiumi, G, Parenzan, P, 2007. Lepidotteri Eteroceri d'Italia, GeometridaeEnnominae I. Natura Edizioni Scientifiche di Alfonso Iorio, Bologna" title="Lepidotteri Eteroceri d'Italia, GeometridaeEnnominae I." year="2007">Flamigni et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
it occurs also further north, up to the Graian Alps and the surroundings of Biella (Pennine Alps); the specimens from the Biella area were examined (without dissection of the genitalia) by the first author during the preparatory work on the first volume on the Italian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duponchel" authorityYear="1845" lsidName="" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ennominae">Ennominae</taxonomicName>
. The geographic position would suggest that specimens from Corsica also belong to this subspecies: this will need to be verified through the examination of the collected material.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="239" type="molecular data">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="239">Molecular data.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="239">
The two barcoded specimens (both from Italy) diverge from those of the taxon 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Fidonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="limbaria" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limbaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">limbaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s. str. (from Germany and Upper Normandy) respectively by 1.2% (Ligurian Alps) and 1.6% (northern Apennines); however, they diverge from one another by 1.6% and cannot be regarded as a &quot;common separate cluster&quot;.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="239" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="239">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="239">
The distribution of the taxa 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Fidonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="delimbaria" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delimbaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">delimbaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Fidonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="rablensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rablensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">rablensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the northern Piedmont is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leraut" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Crocota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crocota pseudotinctaria" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudotinctaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">Crocota pseudotinctaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Leraut, 1999 and 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. tinctaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="tinctaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">C. tinctaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hübner">Huebner</normalizedToken>
, 1799): 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="delimbaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="delimbaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">delimbaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="pseudotinctaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="pseudotinctaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">pseudotinctaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur in the surroundings of Biella, while 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="rablensis" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="rablensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">rablensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and both 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="pseudotinctaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="pseudotinctaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">pseudotinctaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="tinctaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="tinctaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">tinctaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur further to the north-east, in Campello Monti (
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="tinctaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="tinctaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">tinctaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also occurs in Lombardy, like 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="rablensis" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="rablensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">rablensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The analysis of the DNA of the northern Piedmontese populations could help to better understand the relationship between the three taxa present in this area (
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="delimbaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="delimbaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">delimbaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="anzascaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="anzascaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">anzascaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="rablensis" pageId="12" pageNumber="239" rank="species" species="rablensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="239">rablensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); the barcoding of a specimen from Campello Monti was unfortunately not successful.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
